{
  "A food web differs from a food chain because it:": "",
  "Only includes producers and excludes all consumer and decomposer organisms from the diagram": "",
  "Is always shorter in length because it simplifies the number of trophic levels represented": "",
  "Has fewer total organisms because it only tracks one linear pathway of energy transfer": "",
  "Shows the interconnected network of multiple overlapping food chains in an ecosystem": "",
  "A food web is more realistic than a food chain because it shows the complex network of interconnected feeding relationships in an ecosystem, where most organisms eat and are eaten by multiple species.": "",
  "A food chain always begins with:": "",
  "A secondary consumer that feeds on herbivores and occupies the third trophic level of the chain": "",
  "A producer (autotroph) that captures energy from sunlight or chemical reactions": "",
  "A decomposer that breaks down dead organic matter and recycles nutrients back into the soil": "",
  "A top predator that sits at the highest trophic level and regulates populations below it": "",
  "Food chains always begin with producers because they are the organisms that convert inorganic energy (sunlight or chemicals) into organic molecules that all other organisms in the chain depend on.": "",
  "Removing a keystone species from a food web would:": "",
  "Only directly affect the keystone species population itself without impacting other organisms": "",
  "Improve overall ecosystem health by reducing competition for resources among the remaining species": "",
  "Cause dramatic changes in ecosystem structure and potentially lead to species loss throughout the food web": "",
  "Have no measurable effect on the ecosystem because other species can easily fill the vacant niche": "",
  "Keystone species have a disproportionately large effect on their ecosystem relative to their abundance. Removing them causes cascading effects throughout the food web, potentially collapsing entire communities.": "",
  "In a grazing food chain, energy flows from:": "",
  "Predators to prey": "",
  "Decomposers to consumers": "",
  "Living producers to herbivores to carnivores": "",
  "Dead organisms to decomposers": "",
  "A grazing food chain begins with living producers and follows energy through herbivores to carnivores, as opposed to a detrital food chain that begins with dead organic matter.": "",
  "Food chains are typically limited to 4-5 trophic levels because:": "",
  "There are not enough species available in nature to fill additional trophic level positions": "",
  "Ecosystems are physically limited by regulations and cannot have more than five total species": "",
  "The fundamental laws of physics specifically prohibit more than five energy transformation steps": "",
  "Too little energy remains at higher levels to support additional trophic levels (only ~10% is transferred each time)": "",
  "With only about 10% of energy transferred at each level, there is insufficient energy to sustain populations beyond 4-5 trophic levels. This energy limitation fundamentally constrains food chain length.": "",
  "A trophic cascade occurs when:": "",
  "Energy increases at higher trophic levels": "",
  "All organisms in a food web eat the same thing": "",
  "Water flows downhill through an ecosystem": "",
  "Changes at one trophic level trigger reciprocal changes at multiple other trophic levels throughout the food web": "",
  "A trophic cascade is an ecological phenomenon where changes at one trophic level ripple through the food web. For example, removing wolves (top predator) allows elk to overgraze, changing plant communities.": "",
  "An organism that feeds at multiple trophic levels is called:": "",
  "A producer": "",
  "An omnivore": "",
  "A decomposer only": "",
  "A strict herbivore": "",
  "Omnivores eat both plants and animals, functioning at multiple trophic levels. Bears, for example, eat berries (acting as primary consumers) and fish (acting as secondary or tertiary consumers).": "",
  "The detrital food chain begins with:": "",
  "Herbivores that graze on living plant tissues and transfer energy to higher trophic levels": "",
  "Living producers that capture solar energy through photosynthesis and form the base of food webs": "",
  "Top predators that regulate population dynamics through their feeding on lower trophic levels": "",
  "Dead organic matter (detritus) that is consumed by decomposers and detritivores": "",
  "The detrital food chain starts with dead organic matter and flows through detritivores and decomposers. In many ecosystems, more energy flows through the detrital chain than the grazing chain.": "",
  "In a food web, organisms with the most feeding connections are considered:": "",
  "Only found in tropical ecosystems with high biodiversity and year-round warm temperatures": "",
  "The least important organisms for ecosystem stability because they can easily be replaced by others": "",
  "Always apex predators because they sit at the top of the food chain and control all other populations": "",
  "Most important because they provide multiple pathways for energy flow, increasing ecosystem resilience": "",
  "Organisms with many connections in food webs provide redundant energy pathways, making the ecosystem more resilient. If one species declines, energy can flow through alternative routes.": "",
  "When an invasive species enters a food web, it can cause disruption by:": "",
  "Always fitting perfectly into existing niches": "",
  "Having no effect on native food webs": "",
  "Only eating decomposers": "",
  "Outcompeting native species, preying on species with no defenses, and altering food web structure": "",
  "Invasive species disrupt food webs by outcompeting native species for resources, preying on native species that lack defenses, and introducing diseases, often causing cascading effects throughout the ecosystem.": "",
  "What is a food chain?": "",
  "A commercial grocery store supply network that distributes food products to retail consumers": "",
  "A series of sequential cooking steps followed in a recipe to prepare a particular dish": "",
  "A linear sequence showing how energy and nutrients pass from one organism to another through feeding relationships": "",
  "A chain of restaurants that serves food to customers at multiple franchise-owned locations": "",
  "A food chain is a linear pathway showing the transfer of energy and nutrients from one organism to the next, starting with a producer and moving through successive consumers at higher trophic levels.": "",
  "What is a food web?": "",
  "A website that provides information about food, nutrition, and dietary recommendations online": "",
  "A spider web that has been constructed near a convenient food source for capturing insect prey": "",
  "A single linear path of energy flow from one organism to the next in a feeding sequence": "",
  "A complex network of interconnected food chains in an ecosystem showing all feeding relationships": "",
  "A food web is a comprehensive diagram showing all the interconnected feeding relationships in an ecosystem, representing the complex reality that most organisms eat and are eaten by multiple species.": "",
  "What is a keystone species?": "",
  "The most abundant species in an ecosystem": "",
  "A species that has a disproportionately large effect on its ecosystem relative to its abundance": "",
  "Any species that produces its own food": "",
  "A species that lives near a keystone rock formation": "",
  "A keystone species has an outsized impact on ecosystem structure and function relative to its numbers. Removing it causes dramatic changes, like sea stars controlling mussel populations on rocky shores.": "",
  "What is a trophic cascade?": "",
  "A type of disease that spreads through food chains": "",
  "An ecological phenomenon where changes at one trophic level cause rippling effects up or down through multiple trophic levels": "",
  "The gradual erosion of soil in a cascade pattern": "",
  "A waterfall in a tropical forest": "",
  "A trophic cascade occurs when a predator's presence or absence indirectly affects organisms two or more trophic levels away. For example, wolves suppress elk, allowing willow trees to recover along rivers.": "",
  "What is a detrital food chain?": "",
  "A food chain that only exists in deserts": "",
  "A food chain that begins with dead organic matter (detritus) and flows through decomposers and detritivores": "",
  "A food chain that begins with living predators": "",
  "A food chain with no producers": "",
  "A detrital food chain begins with dead organic matter and passes energy through organisms that consume and decompose it. In many forest and marine ecosystems, the detrital chain processes most of the energy.": "",
  "What is an invasive species?": "",
  "Any species that moves to a new location": "",
  "A non-native species introduced to an ecosystem where it causes ecological or economic harm due to lack of natural controls": "",
  "A species that invades other species' nests": "",
  "A species that has always been in its current location": "",
  "An invasive species is a non-native organism that, when introduced to a new environment, spreads rapidly and causes harm because it lacks the natural predators, diseases, or competitors that control it in its native range.": "",
  "What is a generalist species?": "",
  "A species that can survive on a wide variety of food sources and in diverse habitats": "",
  "A military rank within ecology": "",
  "A species that only eats one type of food": "",
  "A species that only lives in one habitat": "",
  "Generalist species like raccoons and crows can thrive in many different environments and eat a wide variety of foods. This flexibility makes them more resilient to environmental changes than specialists.": "",
  "What is a specialist species?": "",
  "A species with a very narrow diet or habitat requirement, making it more vulnerable to environmental changes": "",
  "A species that has been specially trained by scientists to perform tasks in research laboratories": "",
  "A species that can survive and thrive in virtually any habitat or environmental condition": "",
  "The most numerically common and widespread species found in any given ecological community": "",
  "Specialist species depend on specific food sources or habitats, like koalas (eucalyptus leaves only) or giant pandas (bamboo). This narrow niche makes them particularly vulnerable to habitat loss.": "",
  "What is bioaccumulation?": "",
  "The increase in concentration of a substance in an organism over time because it is absorbed faster than it is eliminated": "",
  "The accumulation of soil over time": "",
  "The buildup of biomass at higher trophic levels": "",
  "The accumulation of biodiversity in an area": "",
  "Bioaccumulation is the progressive buildup of substances like pesticides or heavy metals in an individual organism's tissues because the rate of intake exceeds the rate of excretion or metabolism.": "",
  "What is biomagnification?": "",
  "The magnification of biomass at lower trophic levels": "",
  "The increase in organism size at higher trophic levels": "",
  "Viewing organisms under a magnifying glass": "",
  "The increasing concentration of a persistent toxic substance at successively higher trophic levels in a food chain": "",
  "Biomagnification amplifies toxin concentrations up the food chain. Since predators consume many contaminated prey, they accumulate much higher concentrations, which is why DDT devastated apex predators like eagles.": "",
  "When wolves were reintroduced to Yellowstone National Park in 1995, elk populations decreased, which allowed willow and aspen trees to regrow along rivers, stabilizing riverbanks and improving habitat for beavers and fish. This is an example of:": "",
  "A simple food chain with only two trophic levels connecting wolves directly to tree growth": "",
  "An invasive species introduction causing harm to the native ecosystem through competition": "",
  "A trophic cascade, where the top predator's presence caused changes through multiple trophic levels": "",
  "Wolves directly planting trees by burying seeds in the soil throughout the river valley": "",
  "The Yellowstone wolf reintroduction is one of the most famous trophic cascades: wolves reduced elk overgrazing, allowing vegetation recovery that improved habitats for numerous other species.": "",
  "Asian carp were introduced to US waterways and have spread rapidly through the Mississippi River system. They consume large quantities of plankton, outcompeting native fish species. This scenario demonstrates how invasive species disrupt food webs by:": "",
  "Improving the biodiversity of the river system by adding genetic diversity to fish populations": "",
  "Consuming food sources that native species depend on, reducing energy available to native food web members": "",
  "Only affecting the water temperature of the rivers through their large-scale swimming activity": "",
  "Having no measurable impact on native species populations or the local aquatic food web": "",
  "Asian carp disrupt native food webs by consuming massive amounts of plankton that native fish depend on, diverting energy away from native species and causing population declines throughout the food web.": "",
  "Mercury released from a coal-fired power plant enters a lake and is absorbed by algae. Small fish eat algae, larger fish eat small fish, and an osprey eats the larger fish. Mercury concentrations are highest in the osprey. This pattern demonstrates:": "",
  "Biomagnification, where mercury concentration increases at each trophic level of the food chain": "",
  "That ospreys naturally produce mercury": "",
  "That algae are the most contaminated organisms": "",
  "That mercury decreases at higher trophic levels": "",
  "This is biomagnification: mercury accumulates at increasing concentrations up the food chain because predators consume many contaminated prey organisms, concentrating the toxin in their own tissues.": "",
  "Sea otters along the Pacific coast eat sea urchins, which eat kelp. When fur traders nearly eliminated sea otters, sea urchin populations exploded and destroyed kelp forests, which in turn eliminated habitat for hundreds of species. This shows that sea otters are:": "",
  "The only species present in the Pacific kelp forest food web with no other organisms involved": "",
  "A keystone species whose removal causes disproportionate collapse of the entire kelp forest food web": "",
  "Primary producers in the kelp forest ecosystem that create energy through photosynthesis": "",
  "Unimportant to the kelp forest ecosystem because other predators can control urchin populations": "",
  "Sea otters are a classic keystone species. Despite their small population, they regulate sea urchins, which prevents kelp destruction. Without otters, the entire kelp forest ecosystem collapses.": "",
  "A marine biologist notices that a once-diverse coral reef now has only algae after overfishing removed most herbivorous fish. Without herbivores to control algae, corals were smothered. This is an example of:": "",
  "Natural algae growth that occurs completely independently with no connection to fishing pressure": "",
  "Improved reef health resulting from reduced competition between fish species for limited resources": "",
  "Normal coral reef succession that follows a predictable pattern regardless of human intervention": "",
  "A food web disruption where removing one functional group (herbivores) caused a fundamental shift in ecosystem structure": "",
  "Overfishing removed a critical trophic group (herbivorous fish) from the food web. Without grazing pressure on algae, the ecosystem shifted from coral-dominated to algae-dominated, a regime shift.": "",
  "In the Chesapeake Bay, oysters once filtered the entire bay volume every few days, keeping water clear enough for underwater grasses to photosynthesize. Overharvesting of oysters led to murky water, grass die-offs, and fish habitat loss. This scenario shows:": "",
  "That oysters have no role in the food web": "",
  "How a single species can provide critical ecosystem services that maintain the entire food web's structure and function": "",
  "That fishing has no environmental impacts": "",
  "That murky water is the natural state of the bay": "",
  "Oysters performed a critical ecosystem function (water filtration) that sustained the entire food web. Their removal caused cascading effects through water quality, plant communities, and fish populations.": "",
  "A student examines a food web diagram and notices that a mouse is eaten by hawks, snakes, and foxes. If hawks were removed from this food web, the student would predict:": "",
  "All species in the entire food web would immediately go extinct from the loss of one predator": "",
  "Snake and fox populations might initially increase as they face less competition for mouse prey, and mouse populations may temporarily increase before new equilibrium": "",
  "No change would occur in any population because food webs are completely static and unchanging": "",
  "The mouse population would quickly go extinct without hawks to maintain population equilibrium": "",
  "In complex food webs, removing one predator releases prey from some predation pressure. The effect is buffered because other predators (snakes, foxes) still consume mice, demonstrating food web resilience.": "",
  "Brown tree snakes accidentally introduced to Guam have caused the extinction of most native forest bird species. Without birds to disperse seeds and control insects, forests are declining. This demonstrates:": "",
  "That snakes are beneficial to all ecosystems": "",
  "That Guam's ecosystem was already unhealthy": "",
  "That invasive species only affect their direct prey": "",
  "How an invasive predator can collapse entire food webs by eliminating species that provide critical ecological functions": "",
  "The brown tree snake on Guam demonstrates cascading food web effects: eliminating birds removed seed dispersal and insect control, causing indirect impacts on forests that ripple through the entire ecosystem.": "",
  "A lake food web contains: algae, zooplankton, minnows, bass, and eagles. If a disease kills most of the bass, an ecologist would predict:": "",
  "Eagle populations would increase immediately": "",
  "Algae would decrease": "",
  "Minnow populations increase (less predation), leading to zooplankton decline, and possibly increased algae": "",
  "All other populations remain exactly the same": "",
  "Removing bass releases minnows from predation, increasing their numbers. More minnows consume more zooplankton, which reduces grazing on algae, potentially causing algal blooms -- a classic trophic cascade.": "",
  "Scientists studying a grassland find that bison grazing creates patches of short grass preferred by prairie dogs, whose burrow systems aerate soil and create habitat for burrowing owls. Removing bison from the food web would most likely:": "",
  "Increase owl populations because there would be more tall grass providing better cover for nesting": "",
  "Cause prairie dogs to switch their diet from plants to eating bison carcasses left on the plains": "",
  "Have no effect whatsoever on prairie dog or burrowing owl populations in the grassland ecosystem": "",
  "Reduce habitat suitability for prairie dogs and burrowing owls because tall ungrazed grass would replace the short-grass patches they depend on": "",
  "This shows how food web interactions include habitat modification. Bison grazing maintains short grass that prairie dogs need, which in turn supports burrowing owls. These indirect connections reveal food web complexity.": ""
}